# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kubeflow
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:kubeflow/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] Each component of Kubeflow can be deployed separately, and it is not a requirement to deploy every component.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] The Kubeflow project was first announced at *KubeCon + CloudNativeCon North America 2017* by Google engineers David Aronchick, Jeremy Lewi, and Vishnu Kannan to address a perceived lack of flexible options for building production-ready machine learning systems.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] The project has also stated it began as a way for Google to open-source how they ran TensorFlow internally.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] The first release of Kubeflow (Kubeflow 0.1) was announced at *KubeCon + CloudNativeCon Europe 2018*.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] Kubeflow 1.0 was released in March 2020 via a public blog post announcing that many Kubeflow components were graduating to a "stable status", indicating they were now ready for production usage.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] In October 2022, Google announced that the Kubeflow project had applied to join the Cloud Native Computing Foundation.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] In July 2023, the foundation voted to accept Kubeflow as an incubating stage project.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] Machine learning models are developed in the notebooks component called *Kubeflow Notebooks*.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] The component runs web-based development environments inside a Kubernetes cluster, with native support for Jupyter Notebook, Visual Studio Code, and RStudio.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] Once developed, models are trained in the *Kubeflow Pipelines* component.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] The component acts as a platform for building and deploying portable, scalable machine learning workflows based on Docker containers.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] Google Cloud Platform has adopted the *Kubeflow Pipelines DSL* within its *Vertex AI Pipelines* product.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] For certain machine learning models and libraries, the *Kubeflow Training Operator* component provides Kubernetes custom resources support.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] The component runs distributed or non-distributed TensorFlow, PyTorch, Apache MXNet, XGBoost, and MPI training jobs on Kubernetes.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] The *KServe* component (previously named KFServing) provides Kubernetes custom resources for serving machine learning models on arbitrary frameworks including TensorFlow, XGBoost, scikit-learn, PyTorch, and ONNX.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] KServe was developed collaboratively by Google, IBM, Bloomberg, NVIDIA, and Seldon.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] Publicly disclosed adopters of KServe include Bloomberg, Gojek, the Wikimedia Foundation, and others.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] Lastly, Kubeflow includes a component for automated training and development of machine learning models, the *Katib* component.
[src:kubeflow/kubeflow] It is described as a Kubernetes-native project and features hyperparameter tuning, early stopping, and neural architecture search.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:kubeflow/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] The word is a compound of "machine learning" and the continuous delivery practice (CI/CD) of DevOps in the software field.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] Machine learning models are tested and developed in isolated experimental systems.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] When an algorithm is ready to be launched, MLOps is practiced between data scientists, DevOps, and machine learning engineers to transition the algorithm to production systems.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] Similar to DevOps or DataOps approaches, MLOps seeks to increase automation and improve the quality of production models, while also focusing on business and regulatory requirements.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] While MLOps started as a set of best practices, it is slowly evolving into an independent approach to ML lifecycle management.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] MLOps applies to the entire lifecycle - from integrating with model generation (software development lifecycle, continuous integration/continuous delivery), orchestration, and deployment, to health, diagnostics, governance, and business metrics.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] MLOps is a paradigm, including aspects like best practices, sets of concepts, as well as a development culture when it comes to the end-to-end conceptualization, implementation, monitoring, deployment, and scalability of machine learning products.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] Most of all, it is an engineering practice that leverages three contributing disciplines: machine learning, software engineering (especially DevOps), and data engineering.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] MLOps is aimed at productionizing machine learning systems by bridging the gap between development (Dev) and operations (Ops).
[src:kubeflow/mlops] Interest in operationalizing machine learning systems began to grow in the mid-2010s as ML projects started moving from experimentation to production use.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] The challenges associated with sustaining such systems were highlighted in a 2015 paper.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] The predicted growth in machine learning included an estimated doubling of ML pilots and implementations from 2017 to 2018, and again from 2018 to 2020.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] Reports show a majority (up to 88%) of corporate machine learning initiatives are struggling to move beyond test stages.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] However, those organizations that actually put machine learning into production saw a 3–15% profit margin increases.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] The MLOps market size was USD 2,191.8 Million in 2024, and is projected to be USD 16,613.4 Million in 2030.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] Machine Learning systems can be categorized in eight different categories: data collection, data processing, feature engineering, data labeling, model design, model training and optimization, endpoint deployment, and endpoint monitoring.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] Each step in the machine learning lifecycle is built in its own system, but requires interconnection.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] These are the minimum systems that enterprises need to scale machine learning within their organization.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] A standard practice, such as MLOps, takes into account each of the aforementioned areas, which can help enterprises optimize workflows and avoid issues during implementation.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] Vendors such as Adaptive ML deliver commercial reinforcement learning operations (RLOps) and MLOps-infrastructure, targeting organizations deploying large language models in production.
[src:kubeflow/mlops] A common architecture of an MLOps system would include data science platforms where models are constructed and the analytical engines where computations are performed, with the MLOps tool orchestrating the movement of machine learning models, data and outcomes between the systems.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:kubeflow/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:kubeflow/pipeline-computing] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
